Ngozi Uma The focus of Aradhe Cultural festival is to promote unity, revival of cultural heritage of the community and to encourage the youths who have not been visiting home to see the need to do so.Aradhe, a sleeping community in Isoko North Local Government Area of Delta State was in festive mood during the last Yuletide as they celebrated their annual Aradhe Cultural festival which was occasioned with social-cultural entertainment and communal feast. According Mr. Omakopia Felix, the Chairman of the planning committee of the festival, the festival was targeted at reviving the socio-economic and cultural heritage of the people among others, “We want to use the cultural festival for the revival of our heritage, the economic survival of Aradhe through cultural tourism and our local food for outsiders to see and emulate.“Part of the plan of organising the festival was also to encourage Aradhe youths who have not been visiting to see the need to do so, especially those in the Diaspora.‘‘We decided to fix the event during the Yuletide period in order to add colours and glamour to it because of those who came to celebrate Christmas and New year.” he said.Adding that, “Cultural festivals of such nature are basically to foster unity among our children in order for them to see themselves as one big family even if they meet outside.The event that spanned for several days was heralded with a football match and thereafter a seminar where the youths of Aradhe where taken through series of entrepreneurial lectures. They were challenged on productivity and advised to shun criminal activities and be good ambassadors of the community.Some of the youths were also empowered with different working tools in order to enable them start off one business and the other so as to impact on their community and the society at large. The aged and the young also participated in games, there was also free medical care for all. ATPN Set To Launch Lagos Chapter, Hosts Uzamat Akinbile -Yusuf,… TOURISM: Oyo Assures Of Partnership With AACC On Sustainable… Pastor Andrew Osugo, who is the secretary of the planning committee, also disclosed that part of the reasons for the festival was to attract their people in the Diaspora, which he said has been achieved while it has also stimulated the development of the community through the provisions of infrastructure by the wealthy Indigenes.Also speaking at the event, Opa Williams, chairman of Aradhe Gold Cross, said the cultural festival is very important to the people of the community as it helps to preserve their language from going into extinction because most of their children don’t speak the Isoko language anymore.